CCTYPE characters:
******************
cctype library allows to test characters functions tests the character and converts the character case and return a boolean
e.g. of test functions:
isalpha(c) true if c is a letter
isalnum(c) true if c is a letter or number
isdigit()
islower()
isupper()
issspace()
isprint()  ... printable character
ispunct()  ... punctuation character

e.g. of conversion functions:
tolower()  returns a lower case character. if it cant evaluate it returns what you put in.
toupper()


C STYLE STRING:
***************
Sequence of characters
    implemented in a array of characters (constant)
    contiguous in memory -> picture this as 1 character per block/memory address
    terminate with a null character
    referred to as zero or null terminated strings
 string literal
    sequence of characters in double quotes, eg. "Frank"
    constant (size of the array is fixed)
    terminated with null character. eg. 6 characters are assigned for "Frank" even tho is has 5 letters
        if when initialising Frank we give 10 characters, all extra characters are 0s 
    unlike other types if you dont initialse the string as you declare it e.g char my_name [6]; you have to use the
    function strcpy(my_name, "Boris") to initialise it later. using the asignment operator e.g. my_name = "Boris" is wrong
    here, because youre trying to assign one location to another which is illegal (Boris and my_name are both strings and look different)
    therefore leads to -> compiler error 
        the point we're trying to make here does not appy the cctypr characters above 

functions: 
copy strcpy
concatenation strcat
comparison ... 
searching 
and others 